# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quarkus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quarkus/getting-started] In this guide, you’ll create a REST endpoint, see live coding in action, add a service with dependency injection, and write tests.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] You won’t write any boilerplate, and you won’t have to restart the app, not even once.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] To create a Gradle project, add the `--gradle` or `--gradle-kotlin-dsl` option.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] For more information about how to install and use the Quarkus CLI, see the Quarkus CLI guide.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] To create a Gradle project, add the `-DbuildTool=gradle` or `-DbuildTool=gradle-kotlin-dsl` option.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] It imports the Quarkus BOM (`quarkus-bom`), so you can omit the version of Quarkus dependencies in your project.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] It also uses the `quarkus-maven-plugin`, which is responsible for packaging the application and providing development mode.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] It’s a very simple REST endpoint, returning "Hello from Quarkus REST" to requests on "/hello".
[src:quarkus/getting-started] Keep it running and enjoy the blazing fast hot-reload.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] If you really want shutdown the application, hit `CTRL+C`.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] `quarkus:dev` runs Quarkus in development mode.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] Edit your Java files or resource files, save, and refresh your browser, changes take effect immediately, no restart needed.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] If there are any issues with compilation or deployment an error page will let you know.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] Try it: open `src/main/java/org/acme/GreetingResource.java`, change `"Hello from Quarkus REST"` to `"Hola from Quarkus"`, save, and refresh http://localhost:8080/hello.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] Then, switch back to `"Hello from Quarkus REST"`, refresh again… changed again!
[src:quarkus/getting-started] While dev mode is running, open the Dev UI, a dashboard where you can browse installed extensions, configuration, endpoints, and more, all live-updated as you code.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] This will also listen for a debugger on port `5005`.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] If you want to wait for the debugger to attach before running you can pass `-Dsuspend` on the command line.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] If you don’t want the debugger at all you can use `-Ddebug=false`.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] Dependency injection in Quarkus is based on ArC which is a CDI-based dependency injection solution tailored for Quarkus' architecture.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] If you’re new to CDI then we recommend you to read the Introduction to CDI guide.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] Quarkus only implements a subset of the CDI features and comes with non-standard features and specific APIS, you can learn more about it in the Contexts and Dependency Injection guide.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] ArC comes as a dependency of `quarkus-rest` so you already have it handy.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] Let’s modify the application and add a companion bean.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] All right, so far so good, but wouldn’t it be better with a few tests, just in case?
[src:quarkus/getting-started] We also set the `java.util.logging` system property to make sure tests will use the correct log manager and `maven.home` to ensure that custom configuration from `${maven.home}/conf/settings.xml` is applied (if any).
[src:quarkus/getting-started] The generated project contains a simple test.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] These tests use RestAssured, but feel free to use your favorite library.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] You can also run the test from your IDE directly (be sure you stopped the application first).
[src:quarkus/getting-started] By default, tests will run on port `8081` so as not to conflict with the running application.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] We automatically configure RestAssured to use this port.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] The test port can be controlled via the `quarkus.http.test-port` config property.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] You can also have Quarkus run your tests automatically as you code.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] In the dev mode terminal, press `r`, and then Quarkus re-runs affected tests on every save, giving you instant feedback without leaving your editor.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] See the Continuous Testing guide for more details.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] It produces the `quarkus-app` directory in `/target`, which contains the `quarkus-run.jar` file.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] This is a *fast-jar*, not an *über-jar*, the dependencies are copied into subdirectories of `quarkus-app/lib/`.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] You can run the application using: `java -jar target/quarkus-app/quarkus-run.jar`.
[src:quarkus/getting-started] You now have a running Quarkus application with dependency injection and tests.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] It provides additional programming languages and execution modes.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The first production-ready release, GraalVM 19.0, was distributed in May 2019.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The most recent release is GraalVM for JDK 24.0.2, made available in July 2025.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] GraalVM has its roots in the Maxine Virtual Machine project at Sun Microsystems Laboratories (now Oracle Labs).
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The project's goal was to write a Java virtual machine in Java itself to avoid the problems of developing in C++, particularly manual memory management, and benefit from meta-circular optimizations.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The project changed its focus to the compiler and to hook it into the HotSpot runtime as much as possible.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The GraalVM compiler, Graal, was started by manually converting the code of the HotSpot client compiler (named "C1") into Java, replacing the previous Maxine compiler.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] Graal was included in HotSpot-based JDK releases such as OpenJDK from Java SE 9 through 15, to provide experimental ahead-of-time compilation.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The UseJVMCICompiler option also enabled the use of Graal as a replacement for the server compiler (named "C2").
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The option was removed in Java SE 16 to eliminate the duplicate effort of maintaining a version in the JDK and a standalone GraalVM release.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] A similar function to create a native executable from a Java application is provided by the `native-image` tool of standalone GraalVM releases.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The tool processes a Java application's classes and other metadata to create a binary for a specific operating system and architecture.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] It can be used to build a native executable or a native shared library.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] Oracle Corporation announced the release of *Oracle GraalVM Enterprise Edition* on May 8, 2019, and *Oracle GraalVM* on June 13, 2023, introducing a new GraalVM Free Terms and Conditions (GFTC) license.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] GraalVM can substitute for a default JDK on Linux and macOS platforms on x64 and AArch64 CPUs, and on a Windows x64 platform.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The release schedule is at the Oracle Help Center and the GraalVM website.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The GraalVM compiler, Graal, is shipped with the components of a normal Java virtual machine (OpenJDK).
[src:quarkus/graalvm] Additional components are included in GraalVM to enable new execution modes (*GraalVM Native Image*) or programming languages (*LLVM runtime*, *GraalVM JavaScript* as a potential replacement to the deprecated Nashorn engine, *TRegex* as a regular expression engine).
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The GraalVM compiler, Graal, is a modern Java (JIT) compiler.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] It complements or replaces the existing compilers (C1/C2 in HotSpot).
[src:quarkus/graalvm] In contrast to those existing compilers, Graal is written in a modular, maintainable and extendable fashion in Java itself.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] It is released under GPL version 2 with the classpath exception.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] GraalVM Native Image is an ahead-of-time compilation technology that produces executable binaries of class files.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] It is released as an early adopter technology, which means it is production-ready but may include backport incompatible updates in future releases.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] This functionality supports JVM-,based languages, but can optionally run dynamic languages, developed on top of GraalVM with the Truffle framework.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The executable file does not run on a JVM and uses necessary runtime components such as thread scheduling or GC from a minimal bespoke virtual machine called Substrate VM.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] Since the resulting native binary includes application classes, JDK dependencies and libraries already, the startup and execution time are reduced significantly.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] GraalVM Native Image is officially supported by the Fn, Gluon, Helidon, Micronaut, Picocli, Quarkus, Vert.x and Spring Boot Java frameworks.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] In September 2016, Oracle detailed plans to add ahead-of-time compilation to the OpenJDK using the GraalVM compiler for Java SE 9.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] This proposal, tracked by JEP 295: Ahead-of-Time Compilation, was included in Java SE 9.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The experimental use of GraalVM as a just-in-time compiler was added for the Linux x64 platform for Java SE 10.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] In Java SE versions 9 to 15, the `jaotc` command creates an executable.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The experimental `-XX:+EnableJVMCIProduct` flag enables the use of Graal JIT compiler.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The functionality is since available in the Native Image component of standalone GraalVM releases.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] In association with GraalVM, Oracle Labs developed an abstract syntax tree (AST) interpreter called "Truffle" that enables it to implement languages on top of GraalVM.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] Many languages have been implemented in Truffle, including an experimental C interpreter claiming to be about as fast as GCC and Clang.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The Truffle framework and its dependent part, GraalVM SDK, are released under the Universal Permissive License, version 1.0, to encourage the use of the framework for projects that do not want to be bound by the copyright or other parent rights.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] A major advantage of the GraalVM ecosystem is language-agnostic, fully dynamic instrumentation support directly built into the VM runtime.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] Execution events can be captured by API clients with overhead that is extremely low in fully optimized code.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The core GraalVM installation provides a language-agnostic debugger, profiler, heap viewer, and others based on instrumentation and other VM support.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] GraalVM also includes a backend implementation of the Chrome Inspector remote debugging protocol.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] Although designed originally for JavaScript debugging, it can be used to debug all GraalVM languages from a browser.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] Another advantage of GraalVM is the possibility to embed code from a guest language in Java and write "polyglot" applications.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] A developer can integrate JavaScript, Python, or other supported languages inside Java source code, granting them the characteristic advantages of those languages.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] A host Java application and a guest language pass data back and forth in the same memory space.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] It is possible thanks to the Truffle Language Implementation Framework and the GraalVM Polyglot API.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] The Python function increments its input value by one and returns the result to the host language.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] From Java, for security purposes, we ask first if the variable function can be executed via the `canExecute()` call, and then we invoke the function with the `execute()` call.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] Find more examples in the Embedding Languages reference documentation.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] GraalVM is written in and for the Java ecosystem.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] It can run applications written in all languages that compile to the Java bytecode format, for example, Java, Scala, Kotlin, and more.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] Support for additional languages can be implemented by users of GraalVM.
[src:quarkus/graalvm] Some notable third-party language implementations are grCuda, SOMns, TruffleSqueak, and Yona.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] Jakarta EE is defined by its specification.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] The specification defines APIs (application programming interface) and their interactions.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] As with other Java Community Process specifications, providers must meet certain conformance requirements in order to declare their products as *Jakarta EE compliant*.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] Examples of contexts in which Jakarta EE referencing runtimes are used are: e-commerce, accounting, banking information systems.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] The platform created by Sun Microsystems was known as *Java 2 Platform, Enterprise Edition* or *J2EE* from version 1.2, until the name was changed to *Java Platform, Enterprise Edition* or *Java EE* in version 1.5.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] After Sun was acquired in 2009, Java EE was maintained by Oracle under the Java Community Process.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] On September 12, 2017, Oracle Corporation announced that it would submit Java EE to the Eclipse Foundation.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] The Eclipse top-level project has been named Eclipse Enterprise for Java (EE4J).
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] The Eclipse Foundation could not agree with Oracle over the use of `javax` and Java trademarks.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] Oracle owns the trademark for the name "Java" and the platform was renamed from Java EE to Jakarta EE.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] The name refers to the largest city on the island of Java and also the capital of Indonesia, Jakarta.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] The name should not be confused with the former Jakarta Project which fostered a number of current and former Java projects at the Apache Software Foundation.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] Jakarta EE includes several specifications that serve different purposes, like generating web pages, reading and writing from a database in a transactional way, and managing distributed queues.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] The Jakarta EE APIs include several technologies that extend the functionality of the base Java SE APIs, such as Jakarta Enterprise Beans, connectors, servlets, Jakarta Server Pages and several web service technologies.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] In an attempt to limit the footprint of web containers, both in physical and in conceptual terms, the web profile was created, a subset of the Jakarta EE specifications.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] Official Oracle page for Java EE Compatibility.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] Jakarta Mail (formerly JavaMail) is a Jakarta EE API used to send and receive email via SMTP, POP3 and IMAP.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] Jakarta Mail is built into the Jakarta EE platform, but also provides an optional package for use in Java SE.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] The current version is 2.1.3, released on February 29, 2024.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] Another open source Jakarta Mail implementation exists (GNU JavaMail), which -while supporting only the obsolete JavaMail 1.3 specification- provides the only free NNTP backend, which makes it possible to use this technology to read and send news group articles.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] As of 2019, the software is known as Jakarta Mail, and is part of the *Jakarta EE* brand (formerly known as *Java EE*).
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] The reference implementation is part of the Eclipse Angus project.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] Jakarta Mail is hosted as an open source project on Eclipse.org under its new name *Jakarta Mail*.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] The code sample shown below demonstrates how various technologies in Java EE 7 are used together to build a web form for editing a user.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] In Jakarta EE a (web) UI can be built using Jakarta Servlet, Jakarta Server Pages (*JSP*), or Jakarta Faces (*JSF*) with Facelets.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] The example below uses Faces and Facelets.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] Not explicitly shown is that the input components use the Jakarta EE Bean Validation API under the covers to validate constraints.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] To assist the view, Jakarta EE uses a concept called a "Backing Bean".
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] The example below uses Contexts and Dependency Injection (CDI) and Jakarta Enterprise Beans (*EJB*).
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] To implement business logic, Jakarta Enterprise Beans (*EJB*) is the dedicated technology in Jakarta EE.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] For the actual persistence, JDBC or Jakarta Persistence (JPA) can be used.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] Not explicitly shown is that JTA is used under the covers by EJB to control transactional behavior.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] For defining entity/model classes Jakarta EE provides the Jakarta Persistence (*JPA*), and for expressing constraints on those entities it provides the Bean Validation API.
[src:quarkus/jakarta-ee] The example below uses both these technologies.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] GraalVM is a Java Virtual Machine for compiling and running applications written in different languages to a native machine binary.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] GraalVM Community Edition has varying support and licensing requirements.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] Mandrel is a downstream distribution of GraalVM CE, supporting the same capabilities to build native executables but based on the open source OpenJDK.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] Mandrel aims to make GraalVM easy to consume by Quarkus applications by only including GraalVM CE components that Quarkus needs.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] Red Hat began commercial support for using Mandrel to build native Quarkus applications since the Quarkus 1.7 release in October 2020.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] Quarkus was designed around the container-first and Kubernetes-native philosophy, optimizing for low memory usage and fast startup times.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] As much processing as possible is done at build time, including taking a closed-world assumption approach to building and running applications.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] This optimization means that, in most cases, all code that does not have an execution path at runtime isn't loaded into the JVM.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] In Quarkus, classes used only at application startup are invoked at build time and not loaded into the runtime JVM.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] Quarkus also avoids reflection as much as possible, instead favoring static class binding.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] These design principles aim to reduce the size, and ultimately the memory footprint, of the application running on the JVM while also enabling Quarkus to be *natively-native*.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] Quarkus' uses the native image capability of GraalVM to compile JVM bytecode to a native machine binary.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] GraalVM aggressively removes any unreachable code found within the application's source code as well as any of its dependencies.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] Combined with Linux containers and Kubernetes, a Quarkus application runs as a native Linux executable, eliminating the JVM.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] Quarkus rests on an ecosystem of technologies, standards, libraries, and APIs, including Contexts & Dependency Injection (CDI), Jax-rs, Java persistence api (JPA), Java Transaction API (JTA), Apache Camel, and Hibernate.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] Quarkus is an Ahead-of-time compilation (AOT) platform, optimizing code for the JVM as well as compiling to native code for improved performance.
[src:quarkus/quarkus] All of the underlying technologies are AOT-enabled.
